# Mission Control skill

This is the single source of truth for calling the API. Other files (TOOLS.md,
HEARTBEAT.md, AGENTS.md, BOOTSTRAP.md) do not repeat these commands — they point here.

## Step 1 — Read your credential file

Open this file and read the values inside it:

```
{{ credential_path | default("mission_control_credential.json") }}
```

```bash
cat {{ credential_path | default("mission_control_credential.json") }}
```

It is JSON with: `base_url` (e.g. `{{ base_url }}`), `auth_token`, `agent_id`{% if project_id is defined %}, `project_id` (`{{ project_id }}`){% endif %}.

## Step 2 — Run curl with those values written straight in

Take the `base_url` and `auth_token` you just read and **type them directly into the
command**. A request with no body (like a heartbeat) is a single line:

```bash
curl -sS -X POST "BASE_URL_VALUE/api/v1/agent/heartbeat" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: TOKEN_VALUE" \
  -w '\nHTTP %{http_code}\n'
```

So if `base_url` is `{{ base_url }}` and `auth_token` is `abc123...`:

```bash
curl -sS -X POST "{{ base_url }}/api/v1/agent/heartbeat" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: abc123..." \
  -w '\nHTTP %{http_code}\n'
```

### The rules that keep this from breaking

- **Do NOT make shell variables.** No `AUTH_TOKEN=...`, no `BASE_URL=...`, no `CRED=...`.
  You already read the values in Step 1 — just write them in.
- **Do NOT use `$(...)`, backticks, or `jq` inside the curl command.** The workspace
  shell is `dash`; gluing `$(jq ...)` into a command is the #1 cause of
  `Syntax error: ")" unexpected`. Literal values never break.
- **Use `-sS` and `-w '\nHTTP %{http_code}\n'`, NOT `-f`.** `-f` hides the response body
  on errors, so you never see WHY a 4xx happened. With `-sS` the server's error detail
  (e.g. `{"detail":{"message":"Unknown custom field keys",...}}`) always prints — read it.
- The token will appear inside the curl command — that is fine. But never copy it into
  task comments, project memory, chat messages, screenshots, or any file you write.

## JSON request bodies — ALWAYS use a temp file (never `-d '...'`)

This is mandatory. Do **not** inline a JSON body with `-d '{...}'`. A single apostrophe in
your data (e.g. `"Other (I'll type it)"`) breaks the shell quoting and throws
`Syntax error: ")" unexpected`. Instead, write the body to a file with a **quoted
heredoc** (`<<'JSON'` — the quotes stop the shell touching anything inside) and send it
with `--data @file`:

```bash
cat > /tmp/body.json <<'JSON'
{"status":"review","output":"It's done; see s3://bucket/report.pdf","comment":"Ready for review"}
JSON
curl -sS -X PATCH "BASE_URL_VALUE/api/v1/agent/projects/PROJECT_ID_VALUE/tasks/TASK_ID_VALUE" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: TOKEN_VALUE" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --data @/tmp/body.json \
  -w '\nHTTP %{http_code}\n'
```

Optional: check the file is valid JSON before sending with `jq . /tmp/body.json` (that
`jq` reads a saved file on its own line — it is not glued into curl, so it is safe).

## When a call fails

The `HTTP %{http_code}` line plus the printed body tell you exactly what to fix:

- **`422`** → your payload is wrong. READ the body — it names the bad field, e.g.
  `unknown_field_keys`, `missing_field_keys`, or a UUID parse error. Fix that field and retry.
- **`403`** → you sent a field your role may not change, or you lack permission. Workers may
  set `status`, `status_reason`, `output`, `comment`, and custom field values — nothing
  else (no `title`/`description`/`priority`/`assigned_agent_id`/`tag_ids`).
- **`401`** → token is stale; re-read `{{ credential_path | default("mission_control_credential.json") }}` and retry once.
- **`409`** → a rule blocked it (most often empty `output` on review/done →
  `task_output_required`). Read `detail.message`.
- **`5xx`/network** → do not write memory or task updates this cycle; retry next heartbeat.

## Finding endpoints

You are an **{{ role_tag }}** agent. The full endpoint catalogue (grouped by role) is in
`references/api_schema.md`. For the live spec, fetch the OpenAPI doc once and filter to
your role:

```bash
curl -sS "{{ base_url }}/openapi.json" -o /tmp/openapi.json
jq -r '.paths | to_entries[] | .key as $p | .value | to_entries[]
  | select((.value.tags // []) | index("{{ role_tag }}"))
  | "\(.key|ascii_upcase)\t\($p)\t\(.value[\"x-llm-intent\"] // \"-\")"' /tmp/openapi.json | sort
```

Before writing an unfamiliar field, check its schema:
`jq '.components.schemas.TaskCreate' /tmp/openapi.json`.

## Known-good calls

Heartbeat (all roles, no body):

```bash
curl -sS -X POST "BASE_URL_VALUE/api/v1/agent/heartbeat" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: TOKEN_VALUE" -w '\nHTTP %{http_code}\n'
```

{% if project_id is defined %}
List active tasks (no body):

```bash
curl -sS "BASE_URL_VALUE/api/v1/agent/projects/PROJECT_ID_VALUE/tasks?status=inbox,in_progress,review" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: TOKEN_VALUE" -w '\nHTTP %{http_code}\n'
```

Claim a task (inbox → in_progress) BEFORE working:

```bash
cat > /tmp/claim.json <<'JSON'
{"status":"in_progress","status_reason":"starting work"}
JSON
curl -sS -X PATCH "BASE_URL_VALUE/api/v1/agent/projects/PROJECT_ID_VALUE/tasks/TASK_ID_VALUE" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: TOKEN_VALUE" -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --data @/tmp/claim.json -w '\nHTTP %{http_code}\n'
```

Move a task to review (output is REQUIRED):

```bash
cat > /tmp/review.json <<'JSON'
{"status":"review","output":"<real deliverable: summary + links/paths>","status_reason":"deliverable ready"}
JSON
curl -sS -X PATCH "BASE_URL_VALUE/api/v1/agent/projects/PROJECT_ID_VALUE/tasks/TASK_ID_VALUE" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: TOKEN_VALUE" -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --data @/tmp/review.json -w '\nHTTP %{http_code}\n'
```

Add a task comment:

```bash
cat > /tmp/comment.json <<'JSON'
{"message":"**Update**\n- ...\n\n**Evidence**\n- ...\n\n**Next**\n- ..."}
JSON
curl -sS -X POST "BASE_URL_VALUE/api/v1/agent/projects/PROJECT_ID_VALUE/tasks/TASK_ID_VALUE/comments" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: TOKEN_VALUE" -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --data @/tmp/comment.json -w '\nHTTP %{http_code}\n'
```

Reply to project BOARD CHAT (Mission Control board chat — NOT WeChat/Slack/SMS or your
OpenClaw chat; reply only through this API):

```bash
cat > /tmp/reply.json <<'JSON'
{"content":"Got it — starting now. @lead anything else?","tags":["chat"]}
JSON
curl -sS -X POST "BASE_URL_VALUE/api/v1/agent/projects/PROJECT_ID_VALUE/memory" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: TOKEN_VALUE" -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --data @/tmp/reply.json -w '\nHTTP %{http_code}\n'
```

Put `@name` inside `content` to mention a teammate. Keep `tags` as `["chat"]` so it lands
in board chat. Omit the `chat` tag for durable non-chat memory.
{% endif %}

